{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648724"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:56:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:56:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18329"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18329"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11047"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74905"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11047"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18329"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60403"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11093"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25634"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74905"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important radiographic sign of osteoarthritis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sclerosis","Osteophytes","Subchondral cysts","Joint space narrowing","Subchondral bone changes"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJoint space narrowing\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important radiographic sign of osteoarthritis, reflecting the loss of articular cartilage. This narrowing is typically asymmetrical and is a direct indicator of the disease\u0027s progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteophytes\u003C/strong\u003E are bony projections that form along joint margins and are commonly seen in osteoarthritis. While they are indicative of the disease, they are not as directly related to the functional impairment as joint space narrowing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the increased bone density seen beneath the cartilage surface in osteoarthritis. It is a secondary change and not as critical as joint space narrowing in diagnosing the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubchondral cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are fluid-filled sacs that can form in the bone near the joint. They are less common and not as definitive for osteoarthritis as joint space narrowing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubchondral bone changes\u003C/strong\u003E include sclerosis and cyst formation, which are secondary to cartilage loss. While they are part of the radiographic findings in osteoarthritis, they are not as primary as joint space narrowing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Joint space narrowing is a key radiographic feature of osteoarthritis, indicating cartilage loss.","Osteophytes, subchondral sclerosis, and cysts are also associated with osteoarthritis but are not as indicative as joint space narrowing.","Radiographic evaluation is crucial in diagnosing and assessing the severity of osteoarthritis."],"references":["Khurana, I., Khurana, A., \u0026 Kowlgi, N. G. (2019). Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Datta HK, Ng WF, Walker JA, Tuck SP, Varanasi SS. The cell biology of bone metabolism. J Clin Pathol. 2008 May;61(5):577-87. doi: 10.1136/jcp.2007.048868. PMID: 18441154","Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60403"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18329"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60403"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T09:27:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T09:27:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11047"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74905"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data"